Preheat your oven to 220°C. Halve then remove the core from the @yellow pepper{1} and slice into thin strips. Remove the top and bottom from the @courgette{1}. Halve lengthways, then chop widthways into small pieces. Peel and grate all but one @garlic clove{2} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Remove the stalk top and bottom from the @aubergine{1}, then slice it in half lengthways. Slice each half lengthways again into three strips (six strips per aubergine), then chop into roughly 2cm chunks.

Put the pepper, courgette and aubergine on a #baking tray{}, then drizzle over a glug of @olive oil{12%ml}. Season with @salt{} and @black pepper{}. Toss to coat then pop on the top shelf of your #oven{}. Roast until softened and slightly crisp at the edges, about ~{20%minutes}.

Heat a drizzle of @olive oil{} in a #frying pan{} on medium heat. Add the grated garlic and the @smoked paprika{1/2%tsp}, stir together and cook for ~{1%minute}. Add the @chopped tomatoes{1%400g can} and a pinch of @sugar{pinch} (if you have some). Season with @salt{} and @black pepper{}. Lower the heat and simmer, stirring occasionally, until you have a thick tomato sauce, about ~{15%minutes}. Once the veggies are ready, remove them from your oven and turn your #grill{} to high.

Cut the @ciabatta{1} in half lengthways (as if you were making a sandwich). Pop it on another baking tray, place under your grill and toast until golden, ~{1-2%minutes} on each side. Cut the remaining garlic clove in half and rub this across the cut side of the ciabatta. Drizzle over the @olive oil{} and season with a pinch of @salt{} and @black pepper{}.

Tear the @basil{12} leaves and add two-thirds of them to the tomato sauce, along with the veggies. Stir to combine. Serve the smoky ratatouille on a plate and scatter over the remaining basil. Crumble on the @goat's cheese{125%g} and serve with the garlic bread on the side. Enjoy!

> Smoked paprika is most definitely one of our favourite spices. Regular paprika is made by drying peppers in the sun then grinding them to a powder. For the smoked variety, the peppers are dried in smoke sheds using wood such as oak to impart a distinctive flavour. It's a great store cupboard essential and adds a whole new dimension to your cooking. For this recipe, we balanced it against fresh, mild goat's cheese.